		{"id":"02bb45ea00039966","x":3960,"y":-4160,"width":760,"height":640,"type":"text","text":"Dihydrogen Monoxide ($H_2O$)The Setup: 10 electrons. \n\nUsing the 6-31G(d) basis set from our previous context, we have $N = 26$ spin-orbitals.\n\nQubits Required: 26 Qubits.\n\n# Jordan-Wigner: \nTo simulate an electron jumping from the lowest energy core orbital to the highest virtual orbital (orbital 26), JW must apply a string of $Z$-gates across all 25 preceding qubits.\n\nPauli weight = $\\approx 26$. \n\nIn a real quantum algorithm like VQE (Variational Quantum Eigensolver), this creates thousands of sequential CNOT gates. On near-term (NISQ) quantum computers, the hardware noise will destroy the calculation before it finishes.\n\n# Bravyi-Kitaev: \n\nBecause of the binary tree structure, checking the parity of 25 preceding orbitals only requires checking the \"nodes\" that sum up those blocks.\n\nMax Pauli weight = $\\approx \\log_2(26) \\approx \\mathbf{5}$.The Verdict: At $N=26$, BK completely dominates. By squashing a 26-gate operation down to a 5-gate operation, BK drastically reduces the circuit depth, making the exact simulation of water's electronic structure far more feasible on noisy quantum hardware."},
		{"id":"95cf4b50dfb4c4ac","type":"file","file":"Electronic Structure Problem.md","x":-1800,"y":-2148,"width":923,"height":720},
		{"id":"dda67d5e8bd8011e","type":"file","file":"Application of Computational Chemistry - Eigenstates.md","x":1920,"y":-2220,"width":820,"height":851},
		{"id":"4c5a71419fc81684","type":"file","file":"Solving for Singular Hydrogen.md","x":4880,"y":-5180,"width":1220,"height":1720},
		{"id":"23033b6bb71db598","x":3960,"y":-4340,"width":760,"height":100,"type":"text","text":"Comparing this to the single-atom case:1 Hydrogen atom ($N=10, E=1$): $\\binom{10}{1} = 10$ configurations.1 Hydrogen molecule ($N=10, E=2$): $\\binom{10}{2} = 45$ configurations."}
	],
